Question: is the mean 0?

Average difference?

## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range (`geom_bar()`).

  • display sample mean and sample standard deviation

CLT recap

The sample mean

\[m = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}x_i\]

is a random variable

  • mean estimate: \(\widehat{\mu_{m}} = \overline{x}\), which is \(m\)
  • variance estimate: \(\widehat{\sigma_{m}^{2}} = \frac{s^2}{N}\), with \(s^2\) the sample variance
  • standard error (standard deviation of the mean)

\[s_{m} = \frac{s}{\sqrt{N}}\]

  • becomes Gaussian as \(N\to\infty\) (CLT)

The normal distribution

Normally distributed \(X\)

  • continuous state space:

\[X \in \mathbb{R}\]

  • probability:

\[P(x<X\leq x+\mathrm{d}x) = f(x)\mathrm{d}x\] for infinitesimal \(\mathrm{d}x\)

  • \(f(x)\) is the probability density

\[f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}\mathrm{e}^{-\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}}\]

Parameters

  • mean \(\mu\)
  • variance \(\sigma^2\)

  • Estimated Gaussian approximation to the distribution of the sample mean (unnormalised)

Probability that the mean is 0?

Question: with the Gaussian approximation, what is the probability the mean is 0?

Answer: 0

\(p\)-values

Invert the thinking

  • assume the true mean is 0

\[\mu_m=0\]

  • \(z\) is Gaussian approximation to sample mean distribution with mean fixed to 0

\[z \sim \mathcal{N}(0,s_m^2)\]

\(p\)-values

Invert the thinking

  • assume the true mean is 0

\[\mu_m=0 \, , \qquad z \sim \mathcal{N}(0,s_m^2)\]

Question: how do we obtain a probability of observing a sample mean \(m\)?

Answer: we need to select a range of \(z\)

\(p\)-values

Invert the thinking

  • assume the true mean is 0

\[\mu_m=0 \, , \qquad z \sim \mathcal{N}(0,s_m^2)\]

Question: which range should we take?

Answer: more (or as) extreme values than \(\vert m\vert\)

\(p\)-values

The \(p\)-value is the probability of observing a more extreme (or as extreme) sample mean

\[p = P(\vert z \vert \geq \vert m \vert) , \qquad z \sim \mathcal{N}(0,s_m^2)\]

  • assuming the true mean is 0

Question: why take absolute values?

Answer: because the sample mean can be extreme in either direction

Computing \(p\)-values

Define null hypothesis \(H_0\)

  • that there is no effect
  • mean \(\mu_0 = 0\)

Rescale sample mean to obtain \(t\)-statistic

\[t = \frac{m - \mu_0}{s_m} = \sqrt{N} \frac{m-\mu_0}{s}\]

Compute the distribution of \(t\) assuming \(H_0\)

  • \(\mu_m=0\)

But the sample variance and standard error \(s_m\) is a random variable

  • adds variance to \(t\)

Normal data leads to Student-\(t\) distribution

\[t \sim \mathcal{T}_{N-1}\]

The Student-\(t\) distribution

Student-\(t\) distributed \(T\)

  • continuous state space:

\[T \in \mathbb{R}\]

  • probability:

\[P(t<T\leq t+\mathrm{d}t) = f(t)\mathrm{d}t\] for infinitessimal \(\mathrm{d}t\)

  • \(f(t)\) is the probability density

\[f(t) = \frac{\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu+1}{2}\right)}{\sqrt{\pi\nu}\Gamma\left(\frac{\nu}{2}\right)}\left(1+\frac{t^2}{\nu}\right)^{-\frac{\nu+1}{2}}\]

Parameter

  • degrees of freedom \(\nu>0\)

 

  • Becomes Gaussian as \(\nu\to\infty\)

Computing \(p\)-values

Define null hypothesis \(H_0\)

  • that there is no effect
  • mean \(\mu_0 = 0\)

Compute \(t\)-statistic

\[t = \frac{m - \mu_0}{s_m} = \sqrt{N} \frac{m-\mu_0}{s}\]

Follows Student-\(t\) distribution under the null

\[t_0 \sim \mathcal{T}_{N-1}\]

  • if data is normally distributed

 

Question: is the mean 0?

Answer: no (it’s actually -0.25). We can see it is negative better with larger sample sizes.

Computing in R

base R

With the t.test(…) function

# Generate some Gaussian samples with mean -0.25
test_samples <- rnorm(50, mean = -0.25, sd = 1)
  • test if the mean is 0
# Run a t-test with null hypothesis of mean 0
t.test(test_samples)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  test_samples
## t = -3.8539, df = 49, p-value = 0.0003385
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8379003 -0.2635547
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## -0.5507275

Computing in R

With the t.test(…) function

# Generate some Gaussian samples with mean -0.25

  • test if the mean is 0

t.test(test_samples)$statistic

Two sample \(t\)-test in R

base R

With the t.test(…) function

# Generate some Gaussian samples with mean -0.25 and control with mean 0
test_samples <- rnorm(50, mean = -0.25, sd = 1)
control_samples <- rnorm(50, mean = 0, sd = 1)
  • test for a difference in means
# Run a two sample t-test with null hypothesis of equal means
t.test(test_samples, control_samples)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  test_samples and control_samples
## t = -2.6511, df = 97.856, p-value = 0.009358
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.9553229 -0.1373819
## sample estimates:
##    mean of x    mean of y 
## -0.550727492 -0.004375063

Two sample \(t\)-test in R

base R

With the t.test(…) function

# Read in the swiss army data from file
swiss_army_df <- read.csv("./data/Zurich_data.csv")
# use the regression formulation
t.test(Height ~ Sex, swiss_army_df)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Height by Sex
## t = -29.278, df = 1152.2, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group F and group M is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -11.151169  -9.750496
## sample estimates:
## mean in group F mean in group M 
##        161.7041        172.1550

 

  • clear difference in mean heights, and large sample size

Summary

\(p\)-values are a measure of surprise

  • how unusual would the data be under the null?

For normal data the rescaled sample mean

  • follows a Student \(t\)-distribution
  • becomes more normal with larger sample sizes (CLT)

\(t\)-tests can be employed to examine average differences

  • one sample, paired samples and two samples
  • more groups \(\to\) ANOVA

\(t\)-tests assume no outliers and normality

  • can check with EDA and Q-Q plots
